### Representative Path B

You are sitting in your garden in the UK on a warm summer evening. Life continued much as you expected. Singapore occasionally comes up in conversation as an opportunity you once considered but ultimately chose not to pursue.

---

### Representative Path C

You are unpacking the last few boxes in your new home back in the UK. The years in Singapore are behind you. They shaped your finances, your careers and your family, but they were always part of a larger plan. Returning home feels like completing a journey rather than undoing one.

---

## Exploded Inspection

Inspection 1 established the purpose of Establishing Shots.

The important observation here is that the third Establishing Shot represents a lived reality that cannot be confused with either of the others.

It is neither permanent relocation nor remaining at home.

It is its own coherent future.

That is why the Landscape requires three Representative Paths.

---

# Inspection Summary

This inspection demonstrates that the number of Representative Paths is determined by the structure of the decision rather than by the number of obvious options available.

The original prompt appeared to present a binary choice.

Clarification revealed that two fundamentally different long-term philosophies existed within the apparent "move" decision.

The Landscape therefore evolved naturally from two apparent futures into three representative futures.

The third Representative Path was not created by the architecture.

It was discovered through a more faithful understanding of the user's intended decision.


The Landscape must distinguish between observed facts, verified facts, user beliefs and architectural interpretation. It must never silently promote one into another.